d":"Huddington, Worcestershire, Anglie"},"da":{"1395–":"1395–Afdød","1395–Female":"1395–Afdød","1396–Female":"1396–Afdød","1396–Male":"1396–Afdød","1420–Male":"1420–Afdød","1368–Male":"1368–Afdød","1372–Female":"1372–Afdød","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"nl":{"1395–":"1395–Overleden","1395–Female":"1395–Overleden","1396–Female":"1396–Overleden","1396–Male":"1396–Overleden","1420–Male":"1420–Overleden","1368–Male":"1368–Overleden","1372–Female":"1372–Overleden","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"1395–":"1395–Deceased","1395–Female":"1395–Deceased","1396–Female":"1396–Deceased","1396–Male":"1396–Deceased","1420–Male":"1420–Deceased","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","1372–Female":"1372–Deceased","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hodington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Ovington  , which, like <i>Howington</i>, is recorded in North Yorkshire in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ovington","meanings":["English (Durham):","habitational name from Ovington (Durham). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfa</i> + connective <i>-ing-</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","possibly a variant of <b>Ovenden</b>, a habitational name perhaps derived from Ovingdean (Sussex) or Ovenden (Yorkshire). The placename Ovingdean derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ofa</i> or <i>Ūfa</i> + the Old English group name suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The placename Ovenden derives from Old English <i>ofen</i> ‘furnace’ or <i>ofan</i>, <i>ufan</i> ‘over, above’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":60,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Hodington was born in 1395, in Huddington, Worcestershire, England, her father, Thomas Hodington, was 27 and her mother, Joan Thurgrim, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Roger Winter."},"et":{"1395–":"1395–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1395–":"1395–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","1372–Female":"1372–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"1395–":"1395–Décédée","1395–Female":"1395–Décédée","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","1396–Male":"1396–Décédé","1420–Male":"1420–Décédé","1368–Male":"1368–Décédé","1372–Female":"1372–Décédée","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Johanna Hodington est née en 1395, à Huddington, Worcestershire, Angleterre, son père, Thomas Hodington, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Joan Thurgrim, avait 23 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Roger Winter."},"de":{"1395–":"1395–Verstorben","1395–Female":"1395–Verstorben","1396–Female":"13